  "doc_id": "54197",
  "text": "For the biomechanical testing, although the application of a cervical follower load would decrease the ROM under lateral bending of functional spinal units [CITATION_1] , we still adopted a 75 N follower load to increase clinical practicability. Furthermore, there has always been a dispute about using a load-controlled, or displacementcontrolled, protocol during biomechanical testing [CITATION_2] . We deemed it to be the case that the load-controlled testing mode may better reflect the axial load from the weight of the head and muscle forces in the neck, making the testing of spinal specimens a better representation of prevailing physiological functional conditions. Consequently, we adopted the load-controlled testing mode for these biomechanical tests.",
